er Corps.\nCel. Ua\" 3. Walser, osasidered by\nFwar Departmeet sad other hIgh .Gov\n\"ent efelals the meet. e\"ets\norsoenel expert In the United States,\nss left the Bureau of War Risk In\nrtnes., where be bold the ofse as\nersonnel .fleer and assistant d.\nseter. and has returned for duty with\nhe War Departsent.\nCol. Wainer, it Is undoestood, has\n*em assigned to the gigeatie task of\nerganising the quartermaster corps,\nad the work is of such eagnitude\nhat Seeretary of War Baker ordered\nits immediate transfer, despite the\n*forts of Colonel Chomeley-Jones,\nlireeter of the War Risk Bureu, to\notain him.\n\"Colonel Wainer is the most com\nWtent and extraordinary personnel\nxpert In the Uniftd States.\" declared\nirector Chomeloy-Jones today. \"and\nre are more than sorry to Ie him.\nfowevor. he ha left the War Risk\nBureau In such eucellent shape that\nwe will be able to 'sorry on' without\nnuch trouble, although he was only\nFith the bureau a year.\"\nI. W. Buarson, assistant director\nof the War Risk Bureau. has been\nlesignated by Director Chomeley\nrones to All elonel Wainer's place as\npersonnel offcer.\nlations have ehzausted their credits\nhero.\nDiscussing the Proeidentisl cam\npaign. Mr. Vanderlip confessed he\nwas surprised and disappointed that\nneither the Democratic nor Republic.\nLa party had risen to the opportunity\nbefore it.\n\"There was a lamentable lack of\noutstanding statesmanship or na\ntionel leadership shown at the Chi.\nesgo and San Franciseo conventions.\"\nsaid Mr. Vanderlip. \"And I say this\nms a Republican.\n\"As to the Presidency itself. I havb\nne. thought upon that. since Roose\nFelt was President. there has grown\n*p an exaggerated idea of the power\nLnd iiftuence our Chief Eezcutive\nshould exercise. I believe our Presi\nsent should not posess powers of a\nSictator or monarch. The position is\nsn executive one, designed to carry\n)ut the expressed wishes of the ma\nlority of our people-and not to fur\nther the Ideas, elms or