ar really\nis, and are glad to get out. WE\nhang on.\n\"The most embarrassing mo\nment\" for the Prince was when\nBolshevism broke out in Rumania.\n\"At that time we had on Ruman\nian soil forty-four divisions of\nRussian troops, more than a mil\nlion men, armed, in our own coun\ntry. And our total forees amount\ned -to only 200,000 men.\n\"You can imagine the situation,\nwith mor than a million Russian\ntroops suddenly turned into Bol\nshevists, saying to our fourteen\ndivisions, 'why do you fight?\nWhat's the use Come and be\nBolshevists with us and let us all\nenoj ourselves.'\nHowever, we finally got rid of\nthem, and now we view everything\noptimistically. Our country, rap\nidly rising from war conditions,\nsees prosperity increasing every\nday.\"\nThe Prince wishes capitalists of\nthe United States to Iow that\nthey will all be welcome in Ru\nmania if they come to invest their\nmoney developing old, or starting\nnew, enterprises. And Rumania\nwill be delighted to see them make\nani however, will not give\nup control of the sources of na\ntional wealth, oil wells, mines and\nso on, but will be glad to share\nthe national wealth with energetic\nAmericans that choose to help do\nvelop it.\nThre are very good opportuni\nties in Rumania, but TAKE\nMONEY WITH YOU.\nInteresting men met the Ru\nmanian princes at Ambassador\nGerard's dinner. If each had told\nthe prince all that he knows, that\nRumanian monarch would have\ntaken back to Europe some infor\nmation about the United States\nthat, as it is, he will not take\nback.\nThere was Mr. White, man'ager\nof Mr. Cox's campaign, tall, thin,\nforceful, looking something like a\ndetermined Indian chief, and a lit\ntle more like the late fat McCar\nren, of Brooklyn. There was Otto\nH. Kahn, who could buy Rumania,\nor a bit of it.\nThere was Delancey Nicol,\nwho could show the crown prince\nhow to capitalise the country for\na hundred times its debt, and Al\nlen A. Ryan, of the Stutz Comn\npay who could show him how to\nbos h price of Russian bonds,\nand Americans of many other\nkinds, some with fancy decora\ntions, and some with 1nothing but\npearls or diamonds In their demo\ncratic shirt fronts.\nThe prince said he would be\nglad to haye a few million Ameri\ncans know What he had to say, so\nhere in this and other Hearst\nnewspapers, a few millions have\nit.\nVICTORIE NEAR WARSAW\nPolish forces are contInuing their\nsueeee north and west of Warsaw.\nthe lstst Department was advised\ntoday In dispatches from the\nAmerican legation at Warsaw.\nPolish armies were reported be\ntwesn Ciechanov and Mlawe, with\napparent prosects of further sue\neeses. The capture of Austrow and\nBriansk threatens the etiting off of\nseveral red armies to the northeast,\nthe dispatch stated\nGeneral BRuddeny ha. apparently\nabandoned hi. attack on Lemberg\nand is now on, the offensive in the\nLreman of Wassaw. it was reperta,\nWarns Agi\nNEUTRALSINEI\nMAY JNREVOLT\nThreaten to Take Up Sinn Fein\nBanner Unless Britain\nEnds Warfare.\nM401a8d fre. First Fa.J\nmeat to free Mgowi b. bas ad.\ndreased a petitos to tag George at\nDalmoral. In which he declares that\nIf Meowiney dies aU hope of consula\ntien is ended.\nDer*s of poliesmen and other rit\nIsh efistals In Ireland wiU answer\nwith their lives, he predlts. L4ttle\nhope for elomeney .greo the throe.,\nhowever, Is seen In view of IAOrd\n\"ge's anouneed poliey to support\nth'government's Irish appointees In\ntheir policy of eoerotoa ad repree.\nRegardless of its probable effect\nand the unfavorable auspioes under\nwhich it meets, the Dublin conferene\nis important In that it has brought\ntogether elements of Irish life whieb\nhitherto have held aloof froin active\npolitics. Thes include professle I\nmen. members of commercial es,\npeers and lieutenants of counties. and\nclergymen.\nEVZRAaRD N CEAMRMAW.\nWhen the conference began its see\nsons yesterday, Sir Hore Plunkett\nrefused the chairmanship and.Sir Nu\ngent Everard, lieutenant of Meath.\nwas electe